The paper discusses the use of machine learning techniques for obtaining vector representations of generalized graphs while preserving their semantic characteristics. This involves the use of neural encoding architectures and topological properties of the graph. The paper also evaluates the semantic features captured by these representations and investigates new methodologies related to link discovery, entity retrieval, and long-distance queries on large relational datasets. Based on these topics, the most likely sub-categories are machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The use of relational datasets and the investigation of link discovery and entity retrieval suggest a possible sub-category of databases (cs.DB). The use of real datasets and the investigation of long-distance queries suggest a possible sub-category of information retrieval (cs.IR). Finally, the use of neural encoding architectures suggests a possible sub-category of natural language processing (cs.CL).
